And now, here you are, showing spreadsheets, Google Drive links, burned houses, and lost friendships. Your burned house can be rebuilt, your threats will fade, your friendships may return or not â€” but the human cost beyond you is permanent. I empathize with your fear and threats, as a woman I don't discount that. But centering yourself, your pain, and your familyâ€™s honor, while ignoring the permanent human cost around you, is tone-deaf. Why is your story taking precedence over lives lost and grief that cannot be undone? You were not in mortal danger like the people who actually suffered. You were not fighting for your life, your family was not being torn apart in irreparable ways. Or just self-centered?
Real bravery isnâ€™t defending your image â€” itâ€™s facing the bigger picture, acknowledging human cost, listening, and taking responsibility beyond personal hurt. You say youâ€™re under house arrest and that everyoneâ€™s lives are moving forward except yours â€” but there are people who will never return home, families who will never see their loved ones again. I finally watched the whole video and honestly it was so hard to sit through the bullshit, but this is my conclusion. I did not want to make multiple comments, but since comments are heavily monitored or not allowed, I am saying it here. Shrinkhala Khatiwada seems to believe the entire Gen Z protest is about her, when in reality it is not. This protest is about corruption, unemployment, inequality, and the deep frustration of a generation that feels ignored and betrayed by those in power. It is about demanding accountability and a future that does not feel stolen. I also cry when I think about my own death and dying because that is part of being human, but turning a collective struggle into your own personal stage is pure main character syndrome. The energy and sacrifices of these young people deserve to stay focused on the real issues, not get lost in unnecessary self-dramatization.

As an audience, I have to admit that we are often naive and can be easily influenced by what we see on social media. When the â€œnepo babyâ€ trend was rising, your name naturally came into the conversation not just because you were Miss Nepal or because of the things you said in interviews about removing corruption, but also because of the choices you made and the family you are now associated with, who themselves have faced similar reputations.
Your stance during the Kantipur employeesâ€™ protest also created an impression that you stood on the wrong side of things, and perhaps that moment is when the negative perception began to pile up. I acknowledge that your brother has been working hard abroad, living a very different life, and I also acknowledge that you have shared your statements and provided proof of your earnings. But still, proof in the form of documents or statements is one thing transparency through verifiable records like bank statements would make your case stronger and silence doubts. I am not saying this because I assume everything you shared is fake; I am saying it because if you are indeed right, then people need undeniable evidence to see the truth.
I also understand your point that other influencers and public figures should have spoken up for you, but they chose not to. Still, with the kind of platform and influence you hold, you also carry a responsibility to communicate openly and in a timely manner. Yes, you are human and what you went through must have been very difficult, but your silence when accusations were at their peak only made the narrative against you stronger.
Even now, despite the evidence you presented, many will not fully believe you. And the reason is simple you chose to stay silent when things were spiraling out of control, and only now, after so much has already happened, you are clarifying. Maybe you are not manipulating anyone; maybe every word youâ€™ve said is true. But the timing, the delay, and the safe distance you maintained will always raise questions.
